WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.730 --> 00:00:09.180
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:15.269
This is a complete course for the CCNA, Cisco
Certified Network Associate, exam.

00:00:15.269 --> 00:00:21.070
In this video we will cover routing fundamentals,
a very important topic to understand for the

00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:22.410
CCNA exam.

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:27.180
In the Ethernet LAN Switching videos we looked
at how switches forward frames to their proper

00:00:27.180 --> 00:00:28.180
destination.

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:33.570
The process routers use to forward packets
to their proper destination is different,

00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:36.230
and that’s what we’ll look at in this
video.

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:39.880
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:43.570
First I’ll answer the question: what is
routing?

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:47.200
Then we’ll look at the routing table on
a Cisco router.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.880
Switches have MAC address tables, and routers
have routing tables.

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:55.780
It’s very important that you know how to
read a router’s routing table.

00:00:55.780 --> 00:01:01.350
Specifically, we will look at two types of
routes found in a routing table: Connected

00:01:01.350 --> 00:01:03.770
and Local routes.

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:08.689
We will also look at routing fundamentals,
specifically route selection.

00:01:08.689 --> 00:01:13.100
In a router’s routing table, they will usually
have a variety of routes.

00:01:13.100 --> 00:01:16.990
So, how does the router select the correct
route for a packet?

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:20.430
We’ll discuss that in this video.

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:25.640
I want to emphasize that this lesson is extremely
important for the CCNA and for learning networking

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:28.560
in general, and so is the next video.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:34.760
So, take it step by step, take notes, and
ask questions if you need help.

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:40.140
After covering all of the material I will
also show a 1-slide review of everything in

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:44.740
this video, so I hope that will help you review
and remember what you learn.

00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:47.409
Let’s get started.

00:01:47.409 --> 00:01:49.690
So, what is routing?

00:01:49.690 --> 00:01:54.560
Well, when a router receives a packet, it’s
the router’s job to forward it, to send

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:56.380
it, to the correct destination.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:01:59.119
That’s where routing comes in.

00:01:59.119 --> 00:02:03.820
Routing is the process that routers use to
determine the path that IP packets should

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:08.200
take over a network to reach their destination.

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:12.891
And routers store routes to all of their known
destinations in a routing table, which we’ll

00:02:12.891 --> 00:02:15.170
look at soon.

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:19.751
As I mentioned before, switches keep a MAC
address table with their known destination

00:02:19.751 --> 00:02:25.890
MAC addresses, and routers keep a routing
table with their known destination networks.

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:30.040
When routers receive packets, they look in
the routing table to find the best route to

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:32.480
forward that packet.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:37.590
There are two main routing methods, methods
that routers use to learn routes.

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:42.160
One is ‘dynamic routing’, in which routers
use dynamic routing protocols such as OSPF

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:48.610
to share routing information with each other
automatically and build their routing tables.

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:53.860
We will cover dynamic routing protocols such
as OSPF later in the course.

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:56.420
Another type is, static routing.

00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:02.220
In this case, a network engineer or admin
manually configures routes on the router.

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:05.500
We will cover static routing in the next video.

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:10.630
In this video we’re going to cover a kind
of route that doesn’t fit into either category.

00:03:10.630 --> 00:03:13.250
Now, what exactly is a route?

00:03:13.250 --> 00:03:16.700
Basically, it’s an instruction to the router.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:22.080
A route tells the router: to send a packet
to destination X, you should send the packet

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:23.920
to next-hop Y.

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:28.390
And next-hop means the next router in the
path to the destination.

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:33.550
Or, if the destination is directly connected
to the router, send the packet directly to

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:34.900
the destination.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:40.640
Or, if the destination is the router’s own
IP address, receive the packet for yourself,

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:42.430
don’t forward it.

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:47.340
This is how the routing table works, it’s
a set of instructions like this.

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:52.569
To demonstrate routing in this video and the
next one, we will use this example network.

00:03:52.569 --> 00:03:57.560
Actually, in this video we will only look
at one small part of this network.

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:03.750
In the next video we will use the entire network,
but first let me introduce the network.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:07.960
There are four routers connected together,
and they represent a WAN.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:15.030
WAN stands for Wide Area Network, a network
that extends over a large geographical area.

00:04:15.030 --> 00:04:20.670
For example, each of these four routers could
be in different cities or even different countries.

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:26.590
And then, connected to R1 and R4 there are
two LANs, local area networks.

00:04:26.590 --> 00:04:31.750
I’m only showing one PC at each LAN, but
let’s say each of these LANs is a different

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:36.669
office in a different city, so really there
are more hosts in each LAN.

00:04:36.669 --> 00:04:42.670
R2 and R3 probably should have their own connected
LANs too, but just to keep the diagram a bit

00:04:42.670 --> 00:04:45.840
cleaner I’m not showing them here.

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.000
Now let’s look at the IP addresses each
device will be using.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:58.210
For this LAN connected to R1, the network
is 192.168.1.0/24 and R1’s G0/2 interface

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:02.669
IP is .1 and PC1’s IP is .10.

00:05:02.669 --> 00:05:07.490
Then, this WAN connection between R1 and R2
is 12.0/24.

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:13.810
R1 G0/1’s IP is .1 and R2 G0/0’s IP is
.2.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:26.180
This WAN connection between R1 and R3 is 13.0/24,
with R1 G0/0 as .1 and R3 G0/0 as .3.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:37.670
The WAN connection between R2 and R4 is 24.0/24,
with R2 G0/1 as .2 and R4 G0/0 as .4.

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:45.889
Then the final WAN connection, between R3
and R4, is 34.0/24, with R3 G0/1 as .3 and

00:05:45.889 --> 00:05:48.389
R4 G0/1 as .4.

00:05:48.389 --> 00:05:58.650
Then, the LAN connected to R4’s G0/2 interface
is 192.168.4.0/24, with R4 G0/2 as .4 and

00:05:58.650 --> 00:06:01.669
PC4 as .10.

00:06:01.669 --> 00:06:05.710
Notice that I made all of the router IP addresses
the same as their name.

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:12.560
All of R1’s IP addresses are .1, R2’s
IP addresses are .2, R3’s are .3, etc.

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:19.380
Don’t expect IP addresses like this in real
networks, but in lessons and labs I will often

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:24.250
use simple addressing schemes like this to
make it easier to understand.

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:30.290
In the next video, we will configure static
routes on the routers to allow PC1 and PC4

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:33.419
to communicate with each other over the network.

00:06:33.419 --> 00:06:37.730
This video will focus on two types of routes
automatically added to a router’s routing

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:41.520
table, not dynamic routes or static routes.

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:46.770
Okay, before looking at routes let’s configure
the IP addresses.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:51.110
I’ll just show the configurations on R1,
since that’s the router we’ll be focusing

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:53.590
on in this video.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:07:02.810
First I configured its G0/0 interface with
IP ADDRESS 192.168.13.1 255.255.255.0, and

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:06.379
then enabled it with NO SHUTDOWN.

00:07:06.379 --> 00:07:10.000
Then I configured G0/1’s IP address.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.490
Notice that, while I was still in interface
config mode for G0/0, I used the INTERFACE

00:07:15.490 --> 00:07:21.200
G0/1 command directly, without returning to
global config mode first.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:25.800
There is no need to use EXIT to return to
global config mode before entering INTERFACE

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:27.389
G0/1.

00:07:27.389 --> 00:07:32.440
You can use the INTERFACE G0/1 command directly
from interface config mode.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:34.349
I then configured G0/2 as well.

00:07:34.349 --> 00:07:43.830
To confirm, I used SHOW IP INTERFACE BRIEF,
and you can see the IP addresses I just configured.

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:48.240
Of course, I configured the other routers’
IP addresses too, but for the sake of time

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:50.220
I won’t show them here.

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:53.680
As I said, in this video we’ll just focus
on R1.

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:58.180
Now let’s take a look at R1’s routing
table.

00:07:58.180 --> 00:08:03.949
The command is SHOW IP ROUTE, it displays
the router’s routing table.

00:08:03.949 --> 00:08:05.910
And here is the output.

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:10.349
There are two main sections to the output,
the ‘codes’ at the top and the actual

00:08:10.349 --> 00:08:12.569
routes at the bottom.

00:08:12.569 --> 00:08:17.520
The Codes legend in the output of SHOW IP
ROUTE lists the different protocols which

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:21.960
routers can use to learn routes, as well as
the codes that represent them in the routing

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:22.960
table.

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:28.500
I’ve highlighted two in blue here, the first
is L, which means local.

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:33.459
This code is used for routes to the actual
IP address configured on the router’s interface,

00:08:33.459 --> 00:08:37.289
and these routes will have a /32 mask.

00:08:37.289 --> 00:08:41.860
If you look at the routes below, notice there
are three routes with L, that I’ve highlighted

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:43.200
in blue.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:46.610
One for each of R1’s interfaces.

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:49.800
Then there is the C code, which means connected.

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:54.860
These are routes to the network the interface
is connected to, with the actual netmask configured

00:08:54.860 --> 00:08:57.050
on the interface.

00:08:57.050 --> 00:09:00.550
Notice there are also three routes with the
C code in the output below.

00:09:00.550 --> 00:09:07.839
So, even though we haven’t configured any
routes yet on R1, it already has six routes.

00:09:07.839 --> 00:09:12.839
When you configure an IP address on an interface
and enable it with the NO SHUTDOWN command,

00:09:12.839 --> 00:09:17.920
2 routes per interface will automatically
be added to the routing table.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.750
A connected route, and a local route.

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:26.480
Earlier I mentioned that there are two main
types of routing: dynamic routing and static

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:27.750
routing.

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:31.040
These connected and local routes, however,
are neither.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:35.200
They are simply added automatically when an
interface is configured.

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:37.830
These are the routes we will focus on in this
video.

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:41.320
Okay, let me explain these routes in more
detail.

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:50.250
So, I’ve highlighted two of the routes,
one connected route to 192.168.1.0/24 and

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:53.490
one local route to 192.168.1.1/32.

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:59.910
So, a connected route is a route to the network
the interface is connected to.

00:09:59.910 --> 00:10:03.560
R1 G0/2’s IP is 192.168.1.1/24.

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:09.430
What do the red and blue numbers mean here?

00:10:09.430 --> 00:10:16.279
Well, because it’s a /24 address the first
24 bits, the first 3 octets, are the network

00:10:16.279 --> 00:10:17.810
portion of the address.

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:21.110
I’ve highlighted that portion in red.

00:10:21.110 --> 00:10:26.430
Then the last 8 bits, the last octet, is the
host portion of the address, and I’ve highlighted

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:28.440
it in blue.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:36.480
When you change that host portion to all 0s,
the result is 192.168.1.0/24, and notice that’s

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.610
the destination of that connected route.

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:41.100
It’s a route to that network.

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:48.089
So, this provides a route to all hosts in
that network, for example 192.168.1.10, .100,

00:10:48.089 --> 00:10:50.839
.232, etc.

00:10:50.839 --> 00:10:55.019
Any address in that .0/24 range.

00:10:55.019 --> 00:11:01.800
Look back up at the routing table, and notice
that the route says ‘192.168.1.0/24 is directly

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:03.899
connected, gigabitethernet0/2.

00:11:03.899 --> 00:11:10.690
So, R1 knows: if I need to send a packet to
any host in that network, I should send it

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:11.829
out of G0/2.

00:11:11.829 --> 00:11:14.620
Okay, that’s the connected route.

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:18.820
Next, let’s look at the local route in more
detail.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:23.750
A local route is a route to the exact IP address
configured on the interface.

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:30.149
A /32 netmask is used to specify the exact
IP address of the interface.

00:11:30.149 --> 00:11:34.890
/32 means that all 32 bits are fixed, they
can’t change.

00:11:34.890 --> 00:11:45.450
So, even though R1’s G0/2 is configured
as 192.168.1.1/24, the local route is to .1/32,

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:48.380
which specifies only that single address.

00:11:48.380 --> 00:11:52.589
It doesn’t include 192.168.1.2, for example.

00:11:52.589 --> 00:11:58.510
So, with this route R1 knows: if I receive
a packet for this IP address, the message

00:11:58.510 --> 00:11:59.510
is for me.

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:03.670
It’s to my own IP address.

00:12:03.670 --> 00:12:06.990
Just to make things clearer, let me show it
like this.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:12.370
/24 means that the netmask is 255.255.255.0.

00:12:12.370 --> 00:12:17.940
The first 24 bits of the netmask are all 1,
so each octet is 255.

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:20.769
These bits are fixed, they can’t change.

00:12:20.769 --> 00:12:24.280
However the last 8 bits, the last octet, are
not fixed.

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:25.649
They can be any number.

00:12:25.649 --> 00:12:37.060
So, the route for 192.168.1.0/24 matches 192.168.1.0
to 192.168.1.255.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:41.690
That means that if R1 receives a packet with
a destination in that range, it will send

00:12:41.690 --> 00:12:44.410
the packet out of the G0/2 interface.

00:12:44.410 --> 00:12:46.790
Let’s see some examples.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:53.941
A packet with a destination IP address of
192.168.1.2 is a match, because the IP address

00:12:53.941 --> 00:12:57.500
begins with 192.168.1.

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:01.730
Because it’s /24, the first 3 octets have
to match.

00:13:01.730 --> 00:13:06.650
So, R1 would send the packet out of G0/2.

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:13.959
192.168.1.7 would also match this route, so
R1 would forward the packet out of G0/2.

00:13:13.959 --> 00:13:15.769
Likewise 192.168.1.89.

00:13:15.769 --> 00:13:23.300
A packet destined for 192.168.2.1, however,
does not match.

00:13:23.300 --> 00:13:28.329
It cannot use this route, because the destination
does not begin with 192.168.1.

00:13:28.329 --> 00:13:32.810
So, what would R1 do with this packet?

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:37.649
It would send the packet using a different
route, or drop the packet if there is no matching

00:13:37.649 --> 00:13:38.959
route.

00:13:38.959 --> 00:13:44.440
The term ‘match’ is very important and
I will use it a lot in this video and others.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:50.110
A route ‘matches’ a packet’s destination
if the packet’s destination IP address is

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:53.510
part of the network specified in the route.

00:13:53.510 --> 00:14:01.209
Using an example on the right, 192.168.1.2
is part of the 1.0/24 network, so the route

00:14:01.209 --> 00:14:04.579
matches the destination IP.

00:14:04.579 --> 00:14:10.280
Destination 192.168.2.1 is not part of that
network, so the route does not match that

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:11.280
destination IP.

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:18.779
Now, the local route to 192.168.1.1/32 is
simpler.

00:14:18.779 --> 00:14:26.630
Because it’s /32, all bits of the netmask
are 1, so its 255.255.255.255.

00:14:26.630 --> 00:14:31.170
All of these bits are fixed, they can’t
change.

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:40.839
So, 192.168.1.1/32 matches ONLY destination
192.168.1.1, no other IP addresses.

00:14:40.839 --> 00:14:46.110
Okay, we looked at those connected and local
routes that were automatically added to R1’s

00:14:46.110 --> 00:14:49.840
routing table when we configured IP addresses
on its interfaces.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:54.570
Now let’s look at another fundamental concept:
route selection.

00:14:54.570 --> 00:15:05.320
So, R1 has a connected route to 192.168.1.0/24
and a local route to 1.1/32, Let’s say R1

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:11.010
receives a packet and the destination IP is
192.168.1.1.

00:15:11.010 --> 00:15:12.769
Can you see the problem here?

00:15:12.769 --> 00:15:21.450
A packet destined for 1.1 is matched by both
routes: 192.168.1.0/24 and .1/32.

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:27.730
So, which route will R1 use for a packet destined
for 1.1?

00:15:27.730 --> 00:15:32.250
Will it send the packet out of G0/2, or will
it receive the packet, because the packet

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:34.589
is for R1 itself?

00:15:34.589 --> 00:15:38.740
The answer is, it will choose the ‘most
specific’ matching route.

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:45.079
So, I explained what a matching route is,
let’s see what ‘most specific’ means.

00:15:45.079 --> 00:15:56.829
The route to 192.168.1.0/24 includes 256 different
IP addresses, from 192.168.1.0 to .255.

00:15:56.829 --> 00:16:04.920
On the other hand, the route to 1.1/32 includes
only 1 IP address, 192.168.1.1.

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:12.240
It specifies just one IP address, not 256
different IP addresses, so this route is more

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:15.230
specific than the /24 route.

00:16:15.230 --> 00:16:23.220
So, when R1 receives a packet destined for
192.168.1.1, it will select the route to 1.1/32.

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:29.750
So, R1 will receive the packet for itself,
rather than forward it out of G0/2.

00:16:29.750 --> 00:16:34.940
That’s the purpose of Local routes, they
tell the router: keep the packet, don’t

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:36.390
forward it.

00:16:36.390 --> 00:16:41.520
This means R1 will de-encapsulate the packet
and look at the contents inside, because the

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:44.670
contents are addressed to R1 itself.

00:16:44.670 --> 00:16:50.420
So, to summarize: the most specific matching
route means the matching route with the longest

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:51.800
prefix length.

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:58.000
Both parts of that statement are important:
the route must match the packet’s destination,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.450
and it also must have the longest prefix length
out of all of the matching routes.

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:06.250
That is the route that the router will use
for the packet.

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:12.839
Now, let me point out these statements here
in the output of SHOW IP ROUTE on R1.

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:16.370
You might have noticed them and wondered what
exactly they mean.

00:17:16.370 --> 00:17:24.620
The top one says 192.168.1.0/24 is variably
subnetted, 2 subnets, 2 masks.

00:17:24.620 --> 00:17:26.199
What exactly does that mean?

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:31.210
Well, first of all its important to know that
these three lines are not routes.

00:17:31.210 --> 00:17:32.900
They mean the following.

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:39.370
The first line, 1.0/24 is variably subnetted,
2 subnets, 2 masks, means that in the routing

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:46.440
table there are two routes to ‘subnets’
that fit within the 1.0/24 Class A network,

00:17:46.440 --> 00:17:52.070
with two different subnet masks, those being
/24 and /32.

00:17:52.070 --> 00:17:55.990
The other two mean the same thing for their
respective networks.

00:17:55.990 --> 00:18:00.530
To really understand these statements, you
have to understand what a subnet is, but we

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:03.710
haven’t covered subnets yet in the course.

00:18:03.710 --> 00:18:07.000
We will cover subnetting soon, in another
video.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:11.690
For now I just wanted to point out that these
three lines are not routes, so you don’t

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:13.270
get confused by them.

00:18:13.270 --> 00:18:18.080
Generally, you can ignore this output in the
routing table and just focus on the routes

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:19.080
themselves.

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:23.890
Now let’s look at a few examples to practice
route selection.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:29.630
R1 receives a packet destined for 192.168.1.1.

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:34.080
Looking at its routing table, which route
will it select for this packet?

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:36.370
And what will it do with the packet?

00:18:36.370 --> 00:18:40.090
If you want, you can pause the video now to
think about the answer yourself.

00:18:40.090 --> 00:18:45.330
So, we have to find the most specific matching
route in the routing table.

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:52.330
This first packet is destined for 192.168.1.1,
and when R1 checks its routing table it will

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:59.280
see that the most specific match is this one,
to 192.168.1.1/32.

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:04.700
It is a local route, so R1 will receive the
packet for itself.

00:19:04.700 --> 00:19:10.440
Note that this packet matches two routes in
the routing table, the route for 1.0/24 and

00:19:10.440 --> 00:19:17.810
the route for .1/32, but the /32 route is
more specific, so it will be selected.

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:20.910
Here’s another example.

00:19:20.910 --> 00:19:26.539
Packet 2 has a destination IP address of 192.168.13.3.

00:19:26.539 --> 00:19:29.390
Which route will R1 select for this packet?

00:19:29.390 --> 00:19:32.360
And what will it do with the packet?

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:36.930
The most specific matching route, actually
the only matching route for this packet, is

00:19:36.930 --> 00:19:39.140
this connected route to 13.0/24.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:46.590
So, R1 will send the packet to the destination,
which is connected to the G0/0 interface.

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:53.180
Here’s a third packet, destination IP 192.168.1.244.

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:55.460
What will R1 do with this packet?

00:19:55.460 --> 00:20:02.090
The only matching route is this one to 1.0/24,
so R1 will use this route to forward the packet.

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:06.990
It’s a connected route, so R1 will send
the packet to the destination, which should

00:20:06.990 --> 00:20:08.980
be connected to that interface.

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:13.830
And here’s a fourth packet, destined for
192.168.12.1.

00:20:13.830 --> 00:20:18.620
What will R1 do with this packet?

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:24.520
There are two matching routes, but the most
specific one is this Local route for 192.168.12.1/32.

00:20:24.520 --> 00:20:29.409
So, R1 will receive the packet for itself.

00:20:29.409 --> 00:20:33.090
Okay, let’s do one more practice question.

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:38.690
Packet 5 is destined for 192.168.4.10.

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:40.830
What will R1 do with this one?

00:20:40.830 --> 00:20:47.580
Because there are no matching routes in the
routing table, R1 will have to drop this packet.

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:52.211
Unlike switches, which flood frames if they
don’t know where the destination is, routers

00:20:52.211 --> 00:20:53.610
do not.

00:20:53.610 --> 00:20:55.730
Routers never ‘flood’ packets.

00:20:55.730 --> 00:21:00.640
If the router doesn’t have a route to the
packet’s destination, it will drop the packet.

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:07.260
Okay, now let’s try to review everything
in this video in one slide.

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:11.740
This will be just a wall of text, but hopefully
it will help you review what we learned in

00:21:11.740 --> 00:21:14.200
this video.

00:21:14.200 --> 00:21:18.080
Routers store information about destinations
they know in their routing table.

00:21:18.080 --> 00:21:23.410
It’s like a switch’s MAC address table,
but of course it functions differently.

00:21:23.410 --> 00:21:27.330
And when they receive packets, they look in
the routing table to find the best route to

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:29.730
forward the packet.

00:21:29.730 --> 00:21:32.700
Each route in the routing table is an instruction.

00:21:32.700 --> 00:21:39.020
A route says, to reach destinations in network
X, send the packet to next-hop Y, which is

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:41.830
the next router in the path to the destination.

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:45.950
Now, on most routers they will have lots of
routes like this.

00:21:45.950 --> 00:21:49.690
To reach destination X, send packets to next-hop
Y.

00:21:49.690 --> 00:21:54.880
However, in this video we didn’t actually
look at this kind of route.

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:58.270
We looked at connected and local routes.

00:21:58.270 --> 00:22:02.809
Connected routes say: if the destination is
directly connected to this router, send the

00:22:02.809 --> 00:22:09.060
packet directly to the destination Or, if
the destination is your own IP address, receive

00:22:09.060 --> 00:22:11.020
the packet for yourself.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:12.960
This is how a Local route works.

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:17.799
Anyway, the point is that the routing table
is a set of instructions for the router, telling

00:22:17.799 --> 00:22:20.760
it how to forward packets.

00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:26.799
In the next video we will look at how next-hops
work when we learn about static routes.

00:22:26.799 --> 00:22:32.110
When you configure an IP address on an interface
and enable the interface, two routes are automatically

00:22:32.110 --> 00:22:34.480
added to the routing table.

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:39.549
The first is a connected route, indicated
with code C in the routing table.

00:22:39.549 --> 00:22:43.070
It is a route to the network connected to
the interface.

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:51.930
For example, if the interface’s IP is 192.168.1.1/24,
the connected route will be to 1.0/24.

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:57.730
I’m repeating the point above, but it tells
the router: to send a packet to a destination

00:22:57.730 --> 00:23:02.330
in this network, send it out of the interface
specified in the route.

00:23:02.330 --> 00:23:08.080
Then, the other kind of route is a Local route,
indicated by code L in the routing table.

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:12.570
It’s a route to the exact IP address configured
on the interface.

00:23:12.570 --> 00:23:21.289
So, if the interface’s IP is 192.168.1.1/24,
the route will be to 1.1/32.

00:23:21.289 --> 00:23:27.120
A /32 netmask is used to specify just the
one IP address.

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:31.890
This tells the router, packets to this destination
are for you, and you should receive them for

00:23:31.890 --> 00:23:34.179
yourself, not forward them.

00:23:34.179 --> 00:23:38.000
Okay, we also talked about how routes ‘match’
destinations.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:43.730
A route matches a destination if the packet’s
destination IP address is part of the network

00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:46.230
specified in the route.

00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:55.140
For example, a packet to 192.168.1.60 is matched
by a route to 1.0/24, but not by a route to

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:56.140
0.0/24.

00:23:56.140 --> 00:24:02.720
Now, if a router receives a packet and it
doesn’t have a route that matches the packet’s

00:24:02.720 --> 00:24:05.520
destination, it will drop the packet.

00:24:05.520 --> 00:24:09.650
This is different than switches, which flood
frames if they don’t have a MAC table entry

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:12.260
for the destination.

00:24:12.260 --> 00:24:16.900
Final point: if a router receives a packet
and it has multiple routes that match the

00:24:16.900 --> 00:24:21.419
packet’s destination, it will use the ‘most
specific’ matching route to forward the

00:24:21.419 --> 00:24:22.700
packet.

00:24:22.700 --> 00:24:26.720
And the most specific matching route means
the matching route with the longest prefix

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:28.380
length.

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:32.580
This is different than switches, which look
for an exact match in the MAC address table

00:24:32.580 --> 00:24:34.440
to forward frames.

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:38.830
The frame’s destination MAC address must
be the exact same as the entry in the MAC

00:24:38.830 --> 00:24:39.830
address table.

00:24:39.830 --> 00:24:44.200
There’s no concept of ‘most specific match’
in switches.

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:49.049
Okay, so that was a summary of this video,
hopefully it helps you review what you learned

00:24:49.049 --> 00:24:54.529
in this video, because this is important fundamental
information.

00:24:54.529 --> 00:24:57.370
And here are the general topics we covered
in this video.

00:24:57.370 --> 00:25:02.669
I introduced the concept of routing, the process
routers use to determine the path that IP

00:25:02.669 --> 00:25:05.200
packets should take over a network.

00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:09.910
We examined the routing table on a Cisco router,
specifically looking at Connected and Local

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:14.711
routes which are automatically added to the
routing table when you configure an IP address

00:25:14.711 --> 00:25:17.130
on an interface.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:21.960
And we also looked at routing fundamentals,
how routers select which route to use to forward

00:25:21.960 --> 00:25:24.180
a particular packet.

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:28.240
They do that by looking for the most specific
matching route in the routing table.

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:33.460
Now, there’s still lots more to cover about
routing, and in the next video we’ll dig

00:25:33.460 --> 00:25:36.820
deeper into the topic by looking at static
routes.

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:41.440
Okay, now let’s move on to the quiz to test
your understanding of the concepts we covered

00:25:41.440 --> 00:25:42.580
in this video.

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:46.390
Here’s quiz question 1.

00:25:46.390 --> 00:25:51.320
The IP address configured on a router interface
will appear in the routing table as what kind

00:25:51.320 --> 00:25:52.320
of route?

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:57.169
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:25:57.169 --> 00:26:02.170
Okay, the answer is C, local.

00:26:02.170 --> 00:26:07.240
When you configure an IP address on an interface,
two routes are automatically added to the

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:11.210
router’s routing table, assuming the interface
is enabled.

00:26:11.210 --> 00:26:15.149
Note that if the interface is shut down, the
routes won’t appear.

00:26:15.149 --> 00:26:20.190
Anyway, the routes that are automatically
added are a connected route, to the network,

00:26:20.190 --> 00:26:24.300
and a local route, to the exact IP address
configured on the router interface.

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:29.789
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:26:29.789 --> 00:26:31.880
Examine R1’s routing table.

00:26:31.880 --> 00:26:37.919
What will it do when it receives a packet
destined for 192.168.3.25?

00:26:37.919 --> 00:26:44.270
Pause the video now to examine R1’s routing
table and select the best answer.

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:50.520
Okay, the answer is B, it will receive the
packet for itself.

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:58.720
R1 has this local route to 192.168.3.25/32,
which means that this IP address is configured

00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:01.149
on its G0/2 interface.

00:27:01.149 --> 00:27:05.980
So, packets destined for 3.25 are destined
for R1 itself.

00:27:05.980 --> 00:27:10.820
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:27:10.820 --> 00:27:14.960
Which of the following statements about the
behavior of routers and switches are true?

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:16.490
(select two).

00:27:16.490 --> 00:27:20.950
Pause the video now to select the best answers.

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:29.409
Okay, the answers are B and C. Switches flood
frames with an unknown destination.

00:27:29.409 --> 00:27:32.210
Those are called unknown unicast frames.

00:27:32.210 --> 00:27:35.990
Routers, on the other hand, never flood packets.

00:27:35.990 --> 00:27:40.500
Instead of flooding packets with unknown destinations,
the router simply drops them.

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:45.419
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:27:45.419 --> 00:27:49.309
Which two types of routes are automatically
added to the routing table when you configure

00:27:49.309 --> 00:27:52.760
an IP address on an interface and enable it?

00:27:52.760 --> 00:27:57.340
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:57.340 --> 00:28:06.640
Okay, the answer is A: C and L. As shown in
the SHOW IP ROUTE output on the right, C stands

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:10.130
for Connected and L stands for Local.

00:28:10.130 --> 00:28:14.529
These two routes are added when you configure
an IP address on an interface and enable it.

00:28:14.529 --> 00:28:20.039
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:28:20.039 --> 00:28:22.460
Examine R1’s routing table below.

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:29.630
If R1 receives a packet destined for 10.0.1.23,
how many routes match that destination?

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:32.250
And which is the most specific matching route?

00:28:32.250 --> 00:28:39.100
Pause the video now to examine the routing
table and select the best answer.

00:28:39.100 --> 00:28:50.580
Okay, the answer is C. There are two matching
routes: 10.0.1.0/24 and .23/32.

00:28:50.580 --> 00:28:56.830
And the most specific matching route is the
route to .23/32, so that route will be selected.

00:28:56.830 --> 00:29:01.920
It’s a local route, so that means R1 will
receive the packet for itself, it won’t

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:03.630
forward it to another device.

00:29:03.630 --> 00:29:07.000
Okay, that’s all for the quiz and this video.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:12.570
I hope it was helpful, thanks for watching.

